author: ReutersBy Joe Brock; Allison Lampert
title: Boeing workers line up to vote on contract, could strike on Friday | AJOT.COM
text: Boeing's U.S. West Coast factory workers stood in long lines on Thursday to vote on a much-criticized new contract, some loudly calling for a strike, piling pressure on the planemaker as it wrestles with chronic production delays and mounting debt. A potential strike could start on Friday, which would be a big early blow to new CEO Kelly Ortberg, brought on last month to restore faith in the planemaker after a door panel blew off a near-new 737 MAX jet in mid-air in January. Polling will close at 6 p.m. PT and the result will be announced this evening, the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers (IAM) said. If a strike is sanctioned, it could start at midnight. The proposed deal includes a general wage increase of 25%, a $3,000 signing bonus and a pledge to build Boeing's next commercial jet in the Seattle area, provided the program is launched within the four years of the contract. Although the IAM leadership recommended on Sunday that members accept the deal, some workers have responded angrily, with many calling for the originally demanded 40% pay rise and lamenting the loss of an annual bonus. On Thursday, a line of workers waiting to vote snaked along the street outside the union’s offices in Renton, the Seattle suburb where Boeing makes its best-selling 737 jet. Some held signs and others chanted “strike”. All of several Boeing workers who spoke to Reuters said they were voting to strike, and were confident the bulk of union members would do the same, although more than 20 declined to say what they planned. Under complicated union rules, two thirds must vote in favor of a strike for the action to begin. With anything less than that, the contract will go into effect. "I'm ready to go on strike for as long as necessary to get everything that we deserve," said Josh King, a 36-year-old quality inspector. "Normally, a strike doesn't bring a worse offer, it always brings a better offer." In a sign some workers were already preparing for picket lines, one union member left the meeting on Wednesday carrying a placard under her arm that read: "On Strike Against Boeing." Workers have been protesting all week in Boeing factories in the Seattle area that assemble Boeing's MAX, 777 and 767 jets. One member wearing a high-visibility vest shouted, “time to strike, baby!” as he exited the building after casting his vote. Boeing shares closed up 0.9% on Thursday. They are down 36% this year on concerns over safety, production and a $60 billion debt burden. A strike would deepen the financial pain and add to delays in delivering planes to airlines already struggling with capacity shortages. ORTBERG'S PLEA The duration of a potential strike isn't clear. A long strike would weigh not only on Boeing's financials, but on airlines which depend on the planemaker’s jets and suppliers who manufacture parts and components for its aircraft. According to a note from TD Cowen, a 50-day strike could cost Boeing an estimated $3 billion to $3.5 billion of cash flow. The Boeing workers' last strike in 2008 shuttered plants for 52 days and hit revenue by an estimated $100 million per day. S&P Global Ratings said an extended strike could delay the planemaker's recovery and hurt its overall rating. Both S&P and Moody's rate Boeing one notch above junk status. UBS analysts estimated in a note that a short-lived strike that does not disrupt plane deliveries would not impact Boeing’s cash usage. However, a one- to two-month strike resulting in a 50% cut to September to December deliveries would mean a $4 billion cash headwind for Boeing. Michael O'Leary, CEO of Boeing customer Ryanair, said on Thursday that a strike could further delay aircraft deliveries, but added he believed that if it happened, it would be short. "We would like to see the labor agreement sorted." A strike would present Boeing with multiple challenges: it will need to decide how to respond at the bargaining table, after saying it had offered everything it could. It also must find a way to secure factories full of extremely valuable, partially built planes, without union workers to do the job. On Wednesday, Ortberg sent a letter to workers, urging them to approve the deal. "A strike would put our shared recovery in jeopardy, further eroding trust with our customers and hurting our ability to determine our future together," the letter said. Ortberg and Boeing Commercial Airplanes boss Stephanie Pope hit the floor at the company's jet assembly plants in Everett and Renton this week to talk with workers about the proposed deal, a source said. Boeing said the average worker pay of $75,608 would grow to $106,350 by the end of the contract, excluding overtime. Boeing machine repair mechanic Harold Wilson said he had mixed emotions about the contract and wanted to see better pensions and higher wages for younger workers. "I think Boeing will be left struggling again."

title: ¡El Chelsea firma a dos nuevos jugadores por 75 M€!
text:
¡El Chelsea firma a dos nuevos jugadores por 75 M€!
En la recta decisiva de la jornada de este miércoles, el Sporting de Portugal ha anunciado que ha alcanzado un acuerdo con el Chelsea para el traspaso de sus dos jóvenes talentos: Dário Essugo y Geovany Quenda.
Es un secreto a voces que el
Chelsea lleva tiempo apostando claramente por la adquisición de jóvenes talentos, reclutando a varias joyas durante las últimas sesiones del mercado. Sin duda, esta potencia de la Premier League se ha consolidado como uno de los agitadores de cada ventana de fichajes.
Filip Jörgensen, Pedro Neto, Omari Kellyman, Aaron Anselmino, Renato Veiga, Mike Penders, Mathis Amougou, Marcu Guiu y Caleb Wiley se unieron a la larga lista de diamantes en bruto que llegaron durante los últimos meses. En esta ocasión, en Stamford Bridge han culminado un doble golpe en el
Sporting de Portugal.
Dário Essugo y Geovany Quenda, rumbo al Chelsea
Coincidiendo con la sesión nocturna de este miércoles, el cuadro lisboeta ha anunciado que ha llegado a un acuerdo con el Chelsea para los traspasos de
Dário Essugo (20 años) y Geovany Quenda (17 años). Una inversión total que se dispara hasta los 74 M€, destacando que el mediocentro -cedido en la UD Las Palmas- se sumará a los Blues en verano. Por su parte, el aterrizaje del extremo será con vistas al curso 2026-2027.

author: @caras
title: La princesa Leonor cumplió 19 años y su celebración se canceló por la Tormenta Dana | Caras
text:
La princesa Leonor es un gran ejemplo de responsabilidad de la Familia Real de España . La joven cumple con sus deberes reales , mientras continúa con su formación militar. Sin embargo, el pasado 31 de octubre, la heredera al trono celebró su cumpleaños 19 . Si bien se tenía pensado que Leonor pase un gran momento, una situación que atraviesa el país le prohibió pasarlo como esperaba y terminó refugiándose en sus estudios.
La princesa Leonor cumplió 19 años y su celebración no fue como lo esperaba La princesa Leonor cumplió 19 años, el pasado 31 de octubre. Según informaron algunos medios, se tenía pensado una comida con sus padres, su hermana, su abuela, la reina Sofía, y su tía abuela, Irene de Grecia . Además, más tarde, se reuniría con sus amigos para divertirse con otro tipo de celebración, dado que también coincide con la noche de Halloween . En una hipotética lista de invitados, se encontraban sus amistades de su infancia, del Bachillerato Internacional que cursó en Gales, primos, amigos de sus primos y compañeros de instrucción en Zaragoza y Marín .
Sin embargo, la princesa heredera no pudo tener esta celebración ideal. Por el contrario, se considera que pasó el día de su cumpleaños en la Escuela Naval de Marín , para continuar con su formación militar. La semana pasada, Leonor estuvo en Oviedo , protagonizando diferentes actos por los Premios Princesa de Asturias 2024 . Finalmente, regresó a Pontevedra , lugar donde tuvo una pequeña celebración, pero no la que esperaba.
Esto se dio debido a un contexto climático que está viviendo España en estos días. Valencia se enfrenta a uno de los fenómenos más brutales de su historia. La DANA provocó fuertes lluvias y tornados en varias partes del país europeo . Sin embargo, la región en el este ya presenta más de 200 muertes, y decenas de desaparecidos por las graves inundaciones. Debido a esto, los reyes Felipe y Letizia decidieron usar el fin de semana largo para visitar las zonas afectadas y apoyar a las familias.
Ante esta situación, la Princesa Leonor decidió tomarse unas pequeñas vacaciones, pero cerca de sus estudios militares. Si bien la DANA le prohibió la celebración de sus sueños, por su cumpleaños 19, la princesa heredera pudo disfrutar de su día y continuar con sus responsabilidades sin problemas. Hasta el momento, España continúa en una situación inestable por la fuerte tormenta , que se desplaza hacia otras regiones. El Ejército se dirige a los municipios de la provincia de Valencia más afectados por las inundaciones para ayudar a despejar calles y accesos.
A.E

author: zapier
title: Hackers Are Using AI Against You: Here Is How To Protect Yourself
text:
Horror sci-fi scene, with old crumpled newspaper cutting about AI and a pair of human skulls.
gettyAI-based social engineering attacks pose a growing risk as cybercriminals leverage advanced tools to enhance scams. Hacker groups use AI for live deepfake video calls, voice cloning, and AI-generated images to make scams more convincing. These technologies allow for large-scale automation of personalized attacks, increasing their reach and effectiveness.
Social media platforms inadvertently serve as hubs for these criminals, who share scamming scripts and techniques in plain sight. The rise of AI-driven tactics amplifies the psychological and financial harm to victims, making these attacks harder to detect and stop, and demanding urgent global action to combat them.
How Hackers Are Using AI Technology to Outsmart You
AI-driven phishing has become alarmingly convincing, producing personalized emails, text messages, and social media posts that appear to come from trusted sources. These tailored communications target individuals and organizations with uncanny precision, significantly boosting their success rates.
Adding to this arsenal is AI-powered voice cloning, which allows scammers to mimic the voices of trusted individuals or authorities during phone calls. This technique, known as vishing, exploits the trust associated with familiar voices to trick victims into revealing sensitive information or transferring funds.
Deepfake technology is another troubling development. By creating realistic video content, cybercriminals can impersonate individuals during video calls or produce fake videos that seem to originate from credible sources. These tactics add an unsettling level of believability to their schemes.
AI does not stop at crafting messages or creating content—it actively analyzes human responses. By interpreting a victim’s language, tone, and sentiment in real time, attackers can adapt their approach on the fly, making their manipulation more effective.
Moreover, AI can process vast amounts of data from social media, public records, and online activities to build detailed victim profiles. These insights enable attackers to design highly personalized strategies, further increasing the chances of success.
Beyond planning, AI automates key aspects of social engineering campaigns. From identifying potential victims to generating and sending phishing messages and even engaging in real-time conversations, these systems make attacks faster, more efficient, and harder to combat.
While AI equips cybercriminals with powerful tools, it is also an essential weapon for those fighting back. Security researchers and organizations leverage AI to detect and counter these sophisticated attacks. However, the rapid evolution of AI capabilities presents an ongoing challenge, requiring constant vigilance and the continuous improvement of security measures to stay ahead of emerging threats.
Do Not Fall for AI Scams: 7 Essential Tips to Keep Your Data Safe
1. Be cautious of unexpected messages, even if they appear to come from someone you trust. Take the extra step to confirm their legitimacy by using official methods—call them directly, send a personal message, or verify face-to-face if possible. Carefully examine the language and tone of messages for any inconsistencies or signs of AI-generated content.
2. Activate multi-factor authentication (MFA) on your accounts and devices to strengthen your security beyond relying solely on passwords. While not directly tied to AI scams, this simple step makes you a significantly harder target for any type of attack.
3. Stay alert to urgent or high-pressure requests, as these are classic tactics in social engineering scams. This advice applies to all forms of social engineering attacks. Remember, if a message gets your heart racing, it is probably a scam—always fraud.
4. Stay wary of overly personalized messages, as AI can use your online footprint to create highly convincing traps. Remember, every scammer’s goal is to earn your trust—make it your goal to question everything and remain skeptical.
5. Keep yourself updated on the latest AI-driven social engineering tactics and scams. Staying informed is your best defense.
6. Deploy strong security measures like email filtering, web content filtering, and antivirus protection to identify and block potential threats. Still, remember, even the best systems can falter if human error is exploited.
7. Report any suspected social engineering attempts to the appropriate authorities and organizations to aid in identifying and addressing new threats.
